Abstract
This project demonstrates the design and implementation of a responsive, single-page interactive menu application tailored for a modern culinary establishment.
Developed using native front-end web technologies, the application provides an intuitive user interface (UI) designed to bridge the gap between static digital 
menus and dynamic e-commerce platforms.

The architecture leverages modern layout mechanics, specifically CSS Grid with an auto-fill configuration and Flexbox, ensuring flawless visual hierarchy and 
component reflowing across a wide range of display dimensions (desktop to mobile devices). To optimize performance and eliminate server overhead,
user interactivity is handled entirely on the client side. Native JavaScript DOM manipulation enables real-time, zero-latency menu filtering based 
on data attributes, alongside active state triggers for order simulation. The result is a lightweight, accessible, and performant web interface that
emphasizes user experience (UX) and clean, maintainable code architecture.
Key Technical Features
Responsive Multi-Column Layout: Implements CSS Grid with repeat(auto-fill, minmax(400px, 1fr)) to establish a fluid grid that automatically scales and wraps item cards based on viewport width without relying on excessive media queries.

Asynchronous Content Filtering: Utilizes vanilla JavaScript to read custom data-category attributes, dynamically toggling display properties (block vs. none) to filter food and beverage segments instantly without page reloads.

Flexible Component Alignment: Integrates CSS Flexbox within individual menu cards to seamlessly separate content text from action fields (price and interactive buttons), maintaining clean alignment across varying text lengths.

Semantic HTML5 Architecture: Built using clean, search-engine-optimized structure including proper partitioning of structural elements to ensure accessibility compliance.

Interactive Event Handling: Features active state listener triggers on selection tabs and item-level call-to-actions ("Add +") to simulate real-time consumer ordering workflows.
